        "padding_top": 36,
        "padding_bottom": 36
      }
    },
    "image_with_text_wKVLmh": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_CLbqn8": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>Q: </strong>You were named Canada’s first female professional surfer (so cool). What did it feel like receiving that title?</p><p><strong>A</strong>:I haven’t actually thought much about it—but when I do, what comes to mind most is how far Canadian surfing and women’s surfing has come even in my lifetime. I was and am just doing what I love, and it’s amazing to see others doing the same and taking the sport and lifestyle to the next level, and how much women have integrated into the lineups around the world. We belong there, we love it. The ocean is just an amazing place to be.</p><p><strong>Q:</strong> What do you hope the next generation of girls feel when they paddle out?</p><p><strong>A: </strong>I hope they feel confident, free, and completely at home in the ocean. Surfing is such a gift—it teaches resilience, patience, presence and joy. I want them to know that they belong out there, that dreams are valid, and that the ocean has endless lessons and adventures waiting for them, and that hopefully, it will always be there for them. A place of solitude, comfort, opportunity and growth.</p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_CLbqn8"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/IMG_7465.jpg",
        "height": "adapt",
        "desktop_image_width": "medium",
